Many very important annotatione of his Ῑ was obliged to omit, as being above the heads of the studente to whom my edition is offered. It is not, of course, to be inserted that Dr. Reid has sanctioned by his approval every comment on which he has made no remark 3 again, I have not thought it necessary to record his assent to my views except when he has added some- thing of his own. It will be observed that I have sometimes recorded his direct dissent. I think where two views may be held consistently with grammar and sense, there is no reason why both should not be put before both teachers and learners. Many of the letters in this Selection have never been explained before except in the very sparse comments of Schiitz and Billerbeck, so that there may be a positive advantage in putting forward divergent views‚ if both are consistent with grammar and context.
